John Edward: Language skills are important for global citizens
Scottish private schools have remained at the top of the academic excellence rankings and this continued in 2018 with the following outstanding exam results, reinforced by personal and joint success in sport, arts, music and other community activities.
Schools with a total of over 30,000 students across Scotland, represented by the Scottish Council for Private Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best service to their students and their parents.
Private schools aim to prepare students for further and higher education, their chosen profession, and their place as global citizens.
As an education sector that is able to design and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we can see that modern languages continue to be a well-known and desired subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, that goes to his head.
If you talk to him in his language, that goes to his heart."
It is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely solely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s fresh exam results, we can see that the languages at the top of the tables are the ones with the highest rate of passing exams among private schools.
In total, 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages received a high score of A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS schools shows that 72 percent of students received an A in Mandarin, 72 percent of German, 69 percent of French, and 63 percent of Spanish.
This shows that Scottish private schools support foreign languages as vital life skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
The languages that are now among the subject choices in private schools and other school curricula are the same as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering, and mathematics).
A 2014 survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills found that 17% of respondents cited a lack of language skills among the reasons why employers find it difficult to find workers for job vacancies.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly mandatory to prepare young people for their future jobs.
As more promising job offers require language skills, such skills are becoming indispensable in a globalising world.
Regardless of the career choice made, acquiring a second language will give a person a real advantage in the future, since the language skills are lifelong.
Being able to communicate directly with foreign citizens gives a multilingual person an immediate competitive advantage.
According to a survey by YouGov conducted by more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent of respondents do not speak any foreign language well enough to have a conversation about it. The only language with a double-digit percentage of speakers was French with 15 percent.
Therefore, the financing of language learning is important for today's children.
Knowledge of several languages, especially those of emerging economies, gives children a better chance of finding a good job.
In Scotland, different languages are taught at each school.
A number of schools focus more on classical modern languages, while other schools teach languages considered the most important in the UK in terms of 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the interests of the child, private schools always have the possibility to choose between several languages, which are taught by experts in their field.
Scottish Private Schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares and equips children with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds for them.
It can no longer be denied that, in a globalised business environment, languages are crucial to a country's future, which is why this must also be reflected in education.
Modern languages should indeed be considered as “international communication skills”.
Private schools continue to offer choice, diversity and excellence to young Scots.
Il faut bien le faire.
