Here are some important facts about Palu and Donggala on Sulawesi Island:
Palu is the capital of the province of Central Sulawesi, located on a narrow bay off the west coast of the island of Sulawesi, and had an estimated population of 379,800 in 2017.
The city was celebrating its 40th anniversary when it was unexpectedly hit by an earthquake and tsunami.
Donggala regents are an area that extends over 300 km (180 miles) to the northwest of Sulawesi Island.
The Regents, an administrative area under the province's authority, had an estimated 299,200 inhabitants in 2017.
Fishing and agriculture are the main economic activities of the province of Central Sulawesi, especially the Donggala coastal region.
Nickel mining is also important in the province, mainly concentrated on the opposite coast of Morowal, Sulawesi.
According to the Indonesian Disaster Mitigation Agency, tsunamis have hit Palu and Donggala several times over the past 100 years.
In 1938, a tsunami in Donggala killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of houses.
In 1996, a tsunami struck the western part of Donggala, killing nine.
Indonesia is seismically located in the Pacific Ring of Fire and is regularly hit by earthquakes.
Here are some of the biggest earthquakes and tsunamis of recent years:
2004: A major earthquake on the west coast of Aceh Province, Indonesia, on December 26, in northern Sumatra triggered a tsunami that struck 14 countries and killed 226,000 people on the Indian Ocean coast, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: Several strong earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in March and early April.
Hundreds died on the island of Nias off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8-degree earthquake struck the southern half of Indonesia's most populated island of Java, creating a tsunami that struck the southern coast and killed nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6-degree earthquake struck the area near the provincial capital of West Sumatra, Padang.
More than 1,100 people died.
2010: A 7.5-degree earthquake struck one of the Sumatran islands - Mentawai Island, triggering a tsunami up to 10 meters high that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A deep earthquake struck the Pidie Jaya regency in Aceh, sowing destruction and panic, reminding people of the deadly 2004 earthquake and tsunami brought destruction.
There was no tsunami at the time, but more than 100 people died in the collapsed buildings.
2018: Major earthquakes hit the Indonesian tourist island of Lombok, killing more than 500 people, mostly on the north side of the island.
The earthquake destroyed thousands of buildings and temporarily left thousands of tourists stranded.
